        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-12-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-01-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="187" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d187">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On April 5, 1954, the House of Commons adopted an opposition resolution
                    recognizing the threat to civilization posed by the hydrogen bomb and urging
                    that the heads of government of the United <pb facs="0569" n="1383"
                        xml:id="pg_1383"/> States, the United Kingdom, and the Soviet Union meet to
                    reconsider the question of regulation of armaments. During the course of the
                    debate on the motion, British Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1"
                        >Winston S. Churchill</persName> disclosed the provisions of the Quebec
                    Agreement of 1943 For documentation on this episode, see <ref
                        target="frus1952-54v06p1">volume VI</ref>. For the record of the debate in
                    the House of Commons, see <hi rend="italic">H. C. Deb.</hi> 5th series, volume
                    526, cols. 36 ff. For text of the Quebec Agreement, see <ref
                        target="frus1943#pg_1117">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, The Conferences at Washington and
                        Quebec, 1943, pages 1117</ref>–<ref target="frus1943#pg_1119"
                    >1119</ref>.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
